1
00:07:36,883 --> 00:07:38,509
What are they like, these girls?

2
00:07:38,579 --> 00:07:43,281
They're very good. A bit wild.
Spend their money quickly. Work hard.

3
00:07:43,347 --> 00:07:45,288
- Are they literate?
- Some of them.

4
00:07:45,554 --> 00:07:48,271
In and out of reformatories
from the day they were picked up.

5
00:07:48,338 --> 00:07:50,640
Jobs like this. It's degrading.

6
00:07:50,931 --> 00:07:53,386
They shouldn't use human beings
to move earth.

7
00:07:53,490 --> 00:07:54,352
No.

8
00:07:54,483 --> 00:07:55,977
And it's not efficient.

9
00:07:56,083 --> 00:07:58,058
If they were to give me
two more excavators...

10
00:07:58,130 --> 00:07:59,625
...I'd be a year ahead of the plan by now.

11
00:07:59,699 --> 00:08:01,325
You're an impatient generation.

12
00:08:01,428 --> 00:08:02,375
Weren't you?

13
00:08:02,483 --> 00:08:04,305
Yes, we were. Very.

14
00:08:05,204 --> 00:08:09,295
Don't be too impatient, Comrade Engineer,
we've come very far, very fast.

15
00:08:09,363 --> 00:08:10,825
Yes, I know that, Comrade General.

16
00:08:10,900 --> 00:08:13,355
Yes, but do you know what it cost?

17
00:08:14,484 --> 00:08:17,233
There were children in those days
who lived off human flesh.

18
00:08:17,300 --> 00:08:18,347
Did you know that?

19
00:08:27,059 --> 00:08:29,678
What is your interest in this girl,
Comrade General?

20
00:08:30,931 --> 00:08:32,458
She may be my brother's child.

21
00:08:32,532 --> 00:08:34,157
- Yuri Andreyevich?
- Yes.

22
00:08:35,252 --> 00:08:37,356
My half-brother, I should say.

23
00:08:38,483 --> 00:08:39,825
If she is...

24
00:08:40,339 --> 00:08:42,575
...she's also Lara's child.

25
00:08:44,563 --> 00:08:45,840
The Lara?

26
00:08:47,219 --> 00:08:48,496
The Lara, yes.

27
00:08:50,069 --> 00:08:54,574
This is a new edition of the "Lara Poems."

28
00:08:54,675 --> 00:08:58,188
Yes, I know.
We admire your brother very much.

29
00:08:58,292 --> 00:09:00,780
Yes, everybody seems to, now.

30
00:09:01,716 --> 00:09:05,196
Well, we couldn't admire him
when we weren't allowed to read him.

31
00:09:06,004 --> 00:09:06,986
No.

32
00:09:22,132 --> 00:09:23,309
Come in.

33
00:09:28,499 --> 00:09:30,125
I sent for you, Comrade.

34
00:09:31,091 --> 00:09:32,717
You're not in any trouble.

35
00:09:43,987 --> 00:09:46,835
I'm General Yevgraf Andreyevich Zhivago.

36
00:09:48,660 --> 00:09:50,253
I'm looking for someone.

37
00:09:51,572 --> 00:09:53,197
Do you understand?

38
00:09:56,724 --> 00:09:59,570
The person I'm looking for
would be my niece.

39
00:10:03,668 --> 00:10:04,977
Please sit down.

40
00:10:07,924 --> 00:10:09,134
Your name is--

41
00:10:09,236 --> 00:10:11,407
Tonya Komarova, Comrade General.

42
00:10:11,827 --> 00:10:13,802
They found you in Mongolia, didn't they?

43
00:10:14,868 --> 00:10:17,550
- Yes, Comrade General.
- What were you doing there?

44
00:10:17,619 --> 00:10:19,081
I was lost, Comrade General.

45
00:10:19,155 --> 00:10:21,064
How did you come to be lost?

46
00:10:21,843 --> 00:10:22,825
I've forgotten.

47
00:10:22,899 --> 00:10:25,070
Was Komarovsky your father's name?

48
00:10:25,171 --> 00:10:27,081
I suppose so, Comrade General.

49
00:10:27,220 --> 00:10:28,595
You suppose so?

50
00:10:28,981 --> 00:10:30,388
It's a common name.

51
00:10:30,484 --> 00:10:32,339
Do you remember your father?

52
00:10:32,660 --> 00:10:33,674
No.

53
00:10:34,580 --> 00:10:36,718
Do you remember your mother?

54
00:10:37,300 --> 00:10:39,667
Yes, I remember my mother.

55
00:10:39,956 --> 00:10:41,385
What was her name?

56
00:10:42,164 --> 00:10:43,211
"Mammy."

57
00:10:43,476 --> 00:10:47,306
What was she like?
I mean, what did she look like?

58
00:10:48,276 --> 00:10:49,388
Big.

59
00:10:50,195 --> 00:10:51,275
Big?

60
00:10:51,988 --> 00:10:55,119
I was little. She looked big.

61
00:11:02,548 --> 00:11:04,207
- Can you read?
- Yes.

62
00:11:05,588 --> 00:11:09,416
"Lara. A Cycle of Poems, by Y.A. Zhivago."

63
00:11:09,716 --> 00:11:12,171
Not me. My half-brother.

64
00:11:14,324 --> 00:11:16,398
The person I'm looking for...

65
00:11:17,620 --> 00:11:19,628
...would be this man's daughter.

66
00:11:23,924 --> 00:11:25,550
This would be her mother.

67
00:11:28,756 --> 00:11:29,836
"Lara."

68
00:11:32,309 --> 00:11:34,992
Did anybody ever call your mother Lara?

69
00:11:35,764 --> 00:11:38,612
I don't know. I don't think so.

70
00:11:41,940 --> 00:11:43,118
She's nice.

71
00:11:45,460 --> 00:11:47,761
I'm not your niece, Comrade General.

72
00:11:48,308 --> 00:11:50,196
Well, I'm nobody's idea of an uncle.

73
00:11:50,260 --> 00:11:53,522
But if this man were my father,
I should want to know.

74
00:11:54,068 --> 00:11:56,850
Did your mother ever tell you
your father was a poet?

75
00:11:56,916 --> 00:11:58,956
Comrade General, my father wasn't a poet.

76
00:11:59,028 --> 00:12:00,522
What was your father?

77
00:12:00,756 --> 00:12:01,966
Not a poet.

78
00:12:06,485 --> 00:12:08,241
Did you like your father?

79
00:12:08,789 --> 00:12:09,934
I've forgotten.

80
00:12:10,005 --> 00:12:12,045
But you liked your mother?

81
00:12:12,629 --> 00:12:14,035
Yes, of course.

82
00:12:17,332 --> 00:12:20,627
Does the name "Strelnikov"
mean anything to you? "Strelnikov"?

83
00:12:23,668 --> 00:12:24,879
"Varykino"?

84
00:12:25,524 --> 00:12:27,597
That's a place, not a person.

85
00:12:28,597 --> 00:12:29,873
"Gromeko"?

86
00:12:30,100 --> 00:12:31,758
- Gromeko?
- Yes.

87
00:12:34,324 --> 00:12:35,600
You see...

88
00:12:36,404 --> 00:12:38,292
...he lost his mother...

89
00:12:38,645 --> 00:12:40,783
...at about the same age you were...

90
00:12:41,492 --> 00:12:44,754
...when your mother lost you.

91
00:12:47,668 --> 00:12:49,806
And, in the same part of the world.

92
00:14:14,741 --> 00:14:17,905
Now is life's artful triumph
of vanities destroyed...

93
00:14:18,229 --> 00:14:21,131
...for the spirit has vanished
from its tabernacle...

94
00:14:21,332 --> 00:14:22,958
...its clay groweth black.

95
00:14:23,189 --> 00:14:27,083
The vessel is shattered, voiceless,
emotionless, dead.

96
00:14:27,668 --> 00:14:31,379
Committing which unto the grave,
let us beseech the Lord...

97
00:14:32,117 --> 00:14:35,434
...that He will give her eternal rest.

98
00:15:41,461 --> 00:15:42,508
Yuri?

99
00:16:12,406 --> 00:16:15,123
You and your husband will dine with us,
Madame Gromeko.

100
00:16:15,221 --> 00:16:16,531
Thank you, Father.

101
00:16:19,062 --> 00:16:21,004
Will you lie down, then, Yuri?

102
00:16:23,414 --> 00:16:25,999
Your mammy and I were great,
great friends, you know...

103
00:16:26,070 --> 00:16:28,787
...so now we are going to look after you.

104
00:16:29,781 --> 00:16:30,992
Thank you.

105
00:16:35,446 --> 00:16:36,722
That's mother's.

106
00:16:36,918 --> 00:16:38,325
It's yours now.

107
00:16:38,422 --> 00:16:40,210
Yes, Yuri. Mammy left it to you.

108
00:16:40,566 --> 00:16:41,809
In her will.

109
00:16:41,940 --> 00:16:44,591
Do you know what a will is, old chap?

110
00:16:45,077 --> 00:16:46,091
Money.

111
00:16:46,933 --> 00:16:50,381
No, Yuri, just this.
Your daddy has all the money.

112
00:16:50,741 --> 00:16:52,432
Can you play it?

113
00:16:53,429 --> 00:16:56,113
I thought all the people in this part
of the world could play the balalaika.

114
00:16:56,182 --> 00:16:58,254
You don't live here, do you?

115
00:16:58,358 --> 00:16:59,667
No, we live in Moscow.

116
00:16:59,733 --> 00:17:02,701
That's a long way from here,
but you will like Moscow.

117
00:17:03,446 --> 00:17:05,006
- Won't he?
- In a bit.

118
00:17:05,110 --> 00:17:07,598
It takes time
to get used to things, doesn't it?

119
00:17:07,798 --> 00:17:09,522
Mother could play it.

120
00:17:10,454 --> 00:17:13,137
Well, your mother was an artist, Yuri.

121
00:17:13,590 --> 00:17:17,845
She could make this common
little instrument sound like two guitars.

122
00:17:18,198 --> 00:17:19,888
Your mother had a gift.

123
00:17:19,989 --> 00:17:21,713
Perhaps Yuri's got a gift.

124
00:17:21,878 --> 00:17:23,154
Would you like lessons?

125
00:17:23,221 --> 00:17:24,683
I can't play it.

126
00:17:29,814 --> 00:17:31,569
Say good night to Yuri, Tonya.

127
00:17:34,453 --> 00:17:36,428
He's your brother, now.

128
00:17:40,790 --> 00:17:42,164
Good night, Yuri.

129
00:17:42,677 --> 00:17:44,139
Good night, old chap.

130
00:17:44,245 --> 00:17:45,423
Good night.

131
00:18:55,797 --> 00:18:58,318
The Gromekos dldn't know
what to make of hlm.

132
00:18:59,766 --> 00:19:03,028
He made hls reputatlon as a poet
whlle he was studylng to be a doctor.

133
00:19:03,574 --> 00:19:06,476
He sald that poetry was no more
of a vocatlon than good health.

134
00:19:07,095 --> 00:19:08,851
What he needed was a job.

135
00:19:09,078 --> 00:19:10,026
Pretty?

136
00:19:10,806 --> 00:19:11,754
Very.

137
00:19:15,990 --> 00:19:18,957
Yeah. It's their right to be pretty.

138
00:19:21,046 --> 00:19:22,835
What will you do next year, Zhivago?

139
00:19:22,902 --> 00:19:24,692
I thought of doing general practice.

140
00:19:24,759 --> 00:19:26,766
Think about doing pure research.

141
00:19:26,999 --> 00:19:29,300
It's exciting, important, tender, beautiful.

142
00:19:29,783 --> 00:19:30,928
General practice.

143
00:19:31,062 --> 00:19:33,396
Life. He wants to see life. Well...

144
00:19:34,038 --> 00:19:37,333
You'll find that pretty creatures
do ugly things to people.

145
00:21:10,871 --> 00:21:12,180
What's your name?

146
00:21:13,591 --> 00:21:14,518
Antipov.

147
00:21:14,582 --> 00:21:15,564
Address?

148
00:21:15,639 --> 00:21:17,068
15 Patrofka.

149
00:21:17,271 --> 00:21:18,318
I'll have these.

150
00:21:18,391 --> 00:21:20,846
We have permission
from the chief of police.

151
00:21:21,367 --> 00:21:23,538
- Well, you claim them at the station.
- When?

152
00:21:23,607 --> 00:21:25,711
Now if you like.

153
00:21:25,814 --> 00:21:26,992
Very well.

154
00:21:27,830 --> 00:21:29,172
He's my brother.

155
00:21:30,454 --> 00:21:33,750
Well, take him home, Miss.
Before he gets into trouble.

156
00:21:40,055 --> 00:21:41,462
Pasha, please!

157
00:21:41,527 --> 00:21:43,119
It's got to be done.

158
00:21:43,254 --> 00:21:44,945
Pasha, why has it got to be done?

159
00:21:45,014 --> 00:21:47,021
For them. For the Revolution.

160
00:21:47,862 --> 00:21:50,613
- Pasha, they don't want a revolution.
- Yes, they do.

161
00:21:50,679 --> 00:21:52,534
They don't know it yet,
but that's what they want.

162
00:21:52,599 --> 00:21:54,192
Give me some of those, Comrade.

163
00:21:56,119 --> 00:21:59,086
Pasha, are you a Bolshevik?

164
00:21:59,254 --> 00:22:02,484
No. The Bolsheviks don't like me.
And I don't like them.

165
00:22:02,934 --> 00:22:04,625
They don't know right from wrong.

166
00:22:04,727 --> 00:22:07,574
Pasha Antipov, you're an awful prig.

167
00:22:13,527 --> 00:22:15,566
Why did you tell him I was your brother?

168
00:22:16,215 --> 00:22:18,451
Well, what else could I have told him?

169
00:22:18,550 --> 00:22:21,103
You could have told him I was your fiance.

170
00:22:21,367 --> 00:22:23,440
Pasha, don't be silly. I'm--

171
00:22:28,407 --> 00:22:31,341
Monsieur Komarovsky has come to see
my mother on business.

172
00:22:32,791 --> 00:22:34,613
People gossip around here.

173
00:22:34,678 --> 00:22:36,140
It's the system, Lara.

174
00:22:36,310 --> 00:22:38,700
People will be different
after the Revolution.

175
00:22:40,760 --> 00:22:41,872
Will you come?

176
00:22:41,943 --> 00:22:43,252
No, Pasha.

177
00:22:44,888 --> 00:22:48,685
I've got exams to take, Pasha.
I've got to get my scholarship.

178
00:23:12,919 --> 00:23:14,228
Hello, Auntie.

179
00:23:15,127 --> 00:23:16,786
There's a letter for you.

180
00:23:16,919 --> 00:23:18,326
From Paris.

181
00:23:20,343 --> 00:23:21,804
Lovely writing.

182
00:23:21,879 --> 00:23:23,405
She's coming home next month.

183
00:23:23,478 --> 00:23:26,031
Tonya? Oh, that's good!

184
00:23:34,616 --> 00:23:36,820
He does seem to be very well informed.

185
00:23:37,176 --> 00:23:39,313
And such a handsome figure of--

186
00:23:39,863 --> 00:23:42,002
Good evening, Mama. Madame.

187
00:23:42,168 --> 00:23:43,412
Larissa.

188
00:23:43,703 --> 00:23:46,900
You can work in there, dear.
Monsieur Komarovsky's here.

189
00:24:06,071 --> 00:24:07,500
Good evening, Larissa.

190
00:24:08,407 --> 00:24:09,782
Good evening, Monsieur.

191
00:24:15,447 --> 00:24:17,619
He advises some very important people.

192
00:24:17,688 --> 00:24:18,899
Yes, I know.

193
00:24:18,968 --> 00:24:20,942
I believe he has government connections.

194
00:24:21,016 --> 00:24:22,609
I don't know, I'm sure.

195
00:24:22,872 --> 00:24:25,261
Isn't he very expensive?

196
00:24:26,264 --> 00:24:29,232
Monsieur Komarovsky advises me
out of kindness, Baroness.

197
00:24:29,495 --> 00:24:31,252
He was a friend of my late husband.

198
00:24:31,320 --> 00:24:32,629
Oh, I see.

199
00:24:32,728 --> 00:24:33,840
Allow me.

200
00:25:02,648 --> 00:25:04,687
Tuesday, if I can, my dear. Goodbye.

201
00:25:21,815 --> 00:25:23,309
Where did you get this?

202
00:25:23,383 --> 00:25:25,423
A friend gave it to me,
Monsieur Komarovsky.

203
00:25:25,495 --> 00:25:27,600
You're not to go
to this peaceful demonstration.

204
00:25:27,671 --> 00:25:28,303
No, Monsieur.

205
00:25:28,375 --> 00:25:30,514
It may not be as peaceful as they think.

206
00:25:30,744 --> 00:25:34,006
That's all I have to say.
Tell your friend that she's a silly creature.

207
00:25:35,352 --> 00:25:36,627
Yes, Monsieur.

208
00:25:47,416 --> 00:25:48,845
How old are you now?

209
00:25:49,944 --> 00:25:51,406
Seventeen, Monsieur.

210
00:27:03,672 --> 00:27:05,133
A hundred and three.

211
00:27:05,240 --> 00:27:07,989
Oh, dear.
And I was so looking forward to it.

212
00:27:09,304 --> 00:27:11,825
Oh, never mind. I'll be all right here.

213
00:27:12,249 --> 00:27:14,966
You will take Lara, won't you,
Victor Yppolitovich?

214
00:27:15,065 --> 00:27:17,846
It is so stupid of me!
It's her first long gown.

215
00:27:21,272 --> 00:27:23,214
I think you'd better call it right off.

216
00:27:23,288 --> 00:27:24,662
Yes. I'll stay with you.

217
00:27:24,728 --> 00:27:27,696
Nonsense! I'll be perfectly all right.
I've got a book.

218
00:27:27,769 --> 00:27:30,190
It's so disappointing for her,
Victor Yppolitovich.

219
00:27:30,264 --> 00:27:33,712
There's so little opportunity
to mix with good society.

220
00:27:35,385 --> 00:27:37,294
Very well. Get your coat.

221
00:27:38,873 --> 00:27:40,367
We're late, if we're going.

222
00:27:40,441 --> 00:27:42,132
I want to avoid Kropotkin Street.

223
00:28:18,456 --> 00:28:21,970
"Brotherhood and freedom."
Yuri, what splendid words.

224
00:28:23,768 --> 00:28:25,972
"Justice, equality and bread."

225
00:28:27,129 --> 00:28:28,885
Don't you think they're splendid?

226
00:28:28,953 --> 00:28:30,000
Yes, I do.

227
00:28:30,553 --> 00:28:32,179
"Brotherhood and freedom."

228
00:28:32,249 --> 00:28:35,664
Brotherhood and fiddlesticks!
You're frozen through.

229
00:28:36,025 --> 00:28:38,895
You've no right, Annushka. It isn't fair.

230
00:28:43,897 --> 00:28:45,784
We'd given you up, Monsieur.

231
00:28:46,617 --> 00:28:48,722
My niece. Coat, Lara.

232
00:28:53,305 --> 00:28:54,767
Charmante.

233
00:28:55,193 --> 00:28:56,370
Come, my dear.

234
00:29:22,617 --> 00:29:24,373
How's the Foie de Veau, Gascoigne?

235
00:29:24,441 --> 00:29:25,935
As always, Monsieur.

236
00:29:26,041 --> 00:29:28,944
- All right. Not too much--
- Not too much mustard, Monsieur.

237
00:29:31,736 --> 00:29:34,606
- Jambon Farcl en Crote.
- Oul, Mademolselle.

238
00:29:35,704 --> 00:29:36,882
Wine, Monsieur?

239
00:29:37,209 --> 00:29:38,583
A little light wine, yes.

240
00:29:38,649 --> 00:29:40,471
Oul, Monsleur. Mademolselle.

241
00:29:41,561 --> 00:29:44,725
This place must be dreadfully expensive,
Monsieur Komarovsky.

242
00:29:46,297 --> 00:29:47,409
It is.

243
00:29:48,120 --> 00:29:50,095
Why not "Victor Yppolitovich"?

244
00:29:52,057 --> 00:29:53,104
I can't.

245
00:30:20,058 --> 00:30:21,650
Mother made this dress.

246
00:30:22,073 --> 00:30:23,218
Very nice.

247
00:30:24,153 --> 00:30:25,811
She's clever, isn't she?

248
00:30:26,073 --> 00:30:28,757
Your mother? Yes. Fine little woman.

249
00:31:09,914 --> 00:31:12,531
No doubt they'll sing in tune
after the Revolution.

250
00:32:13,049 --> 00:32:14,194
Prepare!

251
00:32:36,058 --> 00:32:37,040
Mount!

252
00:33:47,674 --> 00:33:49,332
Tote sabers!

253
00:35:11,322 --> 00:35:12,784
What, what?

254
00:35:13,082 --> 00:35:14,195
What?

255
00:35:45,531 --> 00:35:47,735
- Good night, dear.
- Good night...

256
00:35:48,379 --> 00:35:49,656
...Victor Yppolitovich.

257
00:36:03,354 --> 00:36:05,591
Go inside your houses, please.

258
00:36:05,787 --> 00:36:08,208
All these people will be taken care of.

259
00:36:08,667 --> 00:36:10,128
Go inside, please.

260
00:36:10,459 --> 00:36:13,109
All these people will be taken care of.

261
00:36:13,434 --> 00:36:14,896
Go inside, please.

262
00:36:21,082 --> 00:36:22,260
Get inside.

263
00:36:25,786 --> 00:36:27,860
Yuri, please. No trouble.

264
00:36:28,155 --> 00:36:30,675
Take him inside, sir,
or I'll put him under arrest.

265
00:36:30,811 --> 00:36:34,488
Yuri, I beg you.
Tonya's coming home tomorrow.

266
00:38:00,122 --> 00:38:01,399
Daddy!

267
00:38:07,292 --> 00:38:08,917
There, now, that's enough.

268
00:38:09,755 --> 00:38:11,861
Your mother, your mother.

269
00:38:14,587 --> 00:38:15,635
Mammy!

270
00:38:23,355 --> 00:38:25,014
Mammy, how are you?

271
00:38:26,299 --> 00:38:28,470
Me? Fit as a fiddle.

272
00:38:29,339 --> 00:38:30,713
Turn 'round.

273
00:38:33,947 --> 00:38:36,086
Well, they've taught her something.

274
00:38:44,378 --> 00:38:46,997
- Look at that!
- Isn't Yuri looking well, Tonya?

275
00:38:48,027 --> 00:38:49,936
Yes. Well, let's get along, dear.

276
00:38:50,011 --> 00:38:51,866
Yes. Run along, you two.

277
00:38:56,476 --> 00:39:00,087
I brought you this. It has a piece in it
about young Russian poets.

278
00:39:00,187 --> 00:39:02,740
Oh, good! Thank you.
Does it mention me?

279
00:39:03,612 --> 00:39:05,751
It begins with you. You're the best.

280
00:39:07,067 --> 00:39:09,173
Very intelligent nation, the French.

281
00:39:09,339 --> 00:39:11,227
They have their heads together.

282
00:39:11,292 --> 00:39:13,332
Yes. They're looking at the paper.

283
00:39:13,884 --> 00:39:15,509
They're head over heels--

284
00:39:15,580 --> 00:39:17,106
Annushka, stop it!

285
00:39:17,979 --> 00:39:20,848
Good marriages are made in Heaven,
or some such place.

286
00:39:30,332 --> 00:39:31,990
Victor Yppolitovich?

287
00:39:35,962 --> 00:39:37,457
I want to talk to you.

288
00:39:38,747 --> 00:39:40,274
No, Pasha.

289
00:39:40,379 --> 00:39:41,841
It's important.

290
00:39:43,644 --> 00:39:44,659
All right.

291
00:39:54,588 --> 00:39:56,115
How did you do it?

292
00:39:56,379 --> 00:39:57,525
I didn't.

293
00:39:58,716 --> 00:39:59,992
A Dragoon did.

294
00:40:01,564 --> 00:40:03,669
Oh, Pasha, darling!

295
00:40:04,253 --> 00:40:05,529
Come, come.

296
00:40:08,603 --> 00:40:10,643
- Where's your mother?
- Asleep.

297
00:40:27,707 --> 00:40:30,009
Pasha, I can't deal with this.

298
00:40:30,172 --> 00:40:31,766
Have you got any iodine?

299
00:40:31,868 --> 00:40:33,527
- Yes, but--
- Get it.

300
00:40:46,139 --> 00:40:47,481
Will it hurt?

301
00:40:49,692 --> 00:40:51,350
Pasha, darling!

302
00:40:53,565 --> 00:40:56,314
Pasha, you must go to a hospital!

303
00:40:57,563 --> 00:40:59,734
I daren't for a day or two.

304
00:41:01,276 --> 00:41:03,927
- Will you do something for me?
- Oh, yes. What?

305
00:41:05,532 --> 00:41:06,939
Hide this.

306
00:41:12,060 --> 00:41:13,684
Oh, throw it away!

307
00:41:13,787 --> 00:41:14,714
No.

308
00:41:15,644 --> 00:41:18,065
There'll be no more
peaceful demonstrations.

309
00:41:18,620 --> 00:41:21,436
There were women and children, Lara,
and they rode them down.

310
00:41:22,076 --> 00:41:24,465
Starving women asking for bread.

311
00:41:24,637 --> 00:41:28,434
On Tamskaya Avenue, the pigs
were eating and drinking and dancing!

312
00:41:29,053 --> 00:41:30,262
Hide it for me.

313
00:41:34,236 --> 00:41:35,895
Thanks, Comrade.

314
00:41:36,188 --> 00:41:38,610
Pasha, darling, I'm not your comrade.

315
00:41:38,716 --> 00:41:39,829
Lara?

316
00:41:44,060 --> 00:41:45,686
- Yes?
- Who is there?

317
00:41:45,757 --> 00:41:47,349
It's only Pasha.

318
00:41:49,244 --> 00:41:51,611
You came in very late last night, dear.

319
00:41:51,708 --> 00:41:53,781
The time went so quickly.

320
00:41:54,236 --> 00:41:55,218
Good.

321
00:41:56,316 --> 00:41:57,909
Are you going to church?

322
00:41:58,300 --> 00:41:59,282
Yes.

323
00:42:10,435 --> 00:42:13,501
You know what our Lord said
to the woman taken in adultery?

324
00:42:14,211 --> 00:42:15,421
Yes, Father.

325
00:42:15,716 --> 00:42:17,538
He said, "Go and sin no more."

326
00:42:17,603 --> 00:42:18,781
And, did she?

327
00:42:20,067 --> 00:42:22,521
- I don't know, Father.
- Nobody does, child.

328
00:42:23,491 --> 00:42:25,182
The flesh is not weak.

329
00:42:25,378 --> 00:42:28,640
It is strong. Only the sacrament
of marriage will contain it.

330
00:42:28,995 --> 00:42:30,173
Remember that.

331
00:42:58,019 --> 00:42:59,099
Monsieur...

332
00:43:00,195 --> 00:43:03,992
It's Number Six, this evening, sir.
The most important person here.

333
00:43:15,203 --> 00:43:16,610
Sorry, I'm late.

334
00:43:17,091 --> 00:43:19,458
I've been waiting nearly an hour, Victor.

335
00:43:19,811 --> 00:43:21,088
Have you ordered?

336
00:43:21,891 --> 00:43:22,720
No.

337
00:43:22,819 --> 00:43:25,208
Well, you should have done.

338
00:43:46,595 --> 00:43:48,024
You chose it, Victor.

339
00:43:52,164 --> 00:43:54,204
You've grown up a lot, haven't you?

340
00:43:55,044 --> 00:43:55,993
Yes.

341
00:43:56,260 --> 00:43:58,049
What did you tell your mama tonight?

342
00:43:58,116 --> 00:43:59,425
Victor, don't!

343
00:44:01,059 --> 00:44:03,394
- May I smoke?
- Yes, of course.

344
00:44:08,067 --> 00:44:11,101
You like it, don't you? Cigar smoke?

345
00:44:12,899 --> 00:44:14,306
Come along, my dear.

346
00:44:15,683 --> 00:44:16,861
Sant!

347
00:44:17,859 --> 00:44:19,168
Sant!

348
00:44:23,171 --> 00:44:24,447
Drink, drink.

349
00:44:25,219 --> 00:44:27,161
Up, up, up.

350
00:44:43,715 --> 00:44:46,715
Where did you tell her
we were going, your mama?

351
00:44:48,164 --> 00:44:49,440
She didn't ask.

352
00:44:49,796 --> 00:44:51,868
- That's because she knows.
- No, she doesn't.

353
00:44:51,940 --> 00:44:54,361
You'd both take an oath she doesn't.
But she does.

354
00:44:54,435 --> 00:44:56,159
And you both know she does.

355
00:44:56,323 --> 00:44:57,501
Victor, don't!

356
00:44:57,859 --> 00:44:58,688
What?

357
00:44:58,756 --> 00:44:59,868
Torment me.

358
00:44:59,939 --> 00:45:03,136
Torment? Oh, what a little hypocrite it is.

359
00:45:06,180 --> 00:45:07,902
I'm going, now, Victor.

360
00:45:08,483 --> 00:45:10,076
Whatever you like, dear.

361
00:45:13,283 --> 00:45:15,617
You see, you'll always come back.

362
00:45:23,300 --> 00:45:24,544
Stay, darling.

363
00:45:27,556 --> 00:45:28,766
Stay.

364
00:46:23,940 --> 00:46:26,177
Wake up! Here, take this.

365
00:46:26,373 --> 00:46:28,445
You show it to someone
if you lose your way.

366
00:46:28,516 --> 00:46:31,679
Professor Boris Kurt. And, you find him.
Now, go on.

367
00:46:32,516 --> 00:46:33,726
Professor Boris Kurt.

368
00:46:49,219 --> 00:46:51,259
But, Boris, this is genius.

369
00:46:51,459 --> 00:46:54,808
Really, I thought it was Rachmaninoff?.
I'm going for a smoke.

370
00:47:04,964 --> 00:47:07,103
And how's the general practitioner?

371
00:47:07,268 --> 00:47:08,991
A bit scared of his finals.

372
00:47:09,188 --> 00:47:11,097
Well, I don't think he need be.

373
00:47:11,332 --> 00:47:14,464
How do you like the idea of marrying
a general practitioner?

374
00:47:14,981 --> 00:47:17,850
I like it very much.
But no general practitioner has asked me.

375
00:47:17,924 --> 00:47:18,720
No?

376
00:47:19,205 --> 00:47:21,310
I thought you nomads were hot-blooded.

377
00:47:21,381 --> 00:47:23,354
A slow lot, these general practitioners.

378
00:47:23,427 --> 00:47:25,849
How do you fancy
a professor of pathology?

379
00:47:26,564 --> 00:47:27,993
Does he write poetry?

380
00:47:28,388 --> 00:47:29,533
Alas, no.

381
00:47:29,956 --> 00:47:32,706
Then I'm afraid it's out of the question.
Excuse me.

382
00:47:42,820 --> 00:47:44,827
That's a marvelous girl, Zhivago.

383
00:47:45,700 --> 00:47:46,977
Yes, I'd noticed.

384
00:47:48,739 --> 00:47:50,050
It's for you.

385
00:48:08,452 --> 00:48:11,136
How would the poet like to see
a bit of general practice?

386
00:48:15,076 --> 00:48:18,305
Boris, thank God you've come.
This is very good of you, Boris.

387
00:48:18,372 --> 00:48:20,576
Yes, I know it is. My assistant.

388
00:48:20,676 --> 00:48:22,170
- How do you do?
- Where is she?

389
00:48:22,244 --> 00:48:23,357
This way.

390
00:48:38,116 --> 00:48:39,229
When did she do it?

391
00:48:39,301 --> 00:48:41,309
About eight o'clock this evening.

392
00:48:46,116 --> 00:48:47,458
Do you know what it was?

393
00:48:52,549 --> 00:48:54,273
Why didn't you get a local doctor?

394
00:48:54,341 --> 00:48:56,381
- I couldn't.
- No, I suppose you couldn't.

395
00:48:56,453 --> 00:48:57,500
Come on in.

396
00:48:59,461 --> 00:49:00,738
Turn her over.

397
00:49:05,989 --> 00:49:07,003
All right.

398
00:49:09,444 --> 00:49:10,338
Water.

399
00:49:25,316 --> 00:49:28,099
Now, Yuri. Come on, dear. Come on.

400
00:49:29,157 --> 00:49:30,368
Now, Yuri.

401
00:49:32,006 --> 00:49:33,216
Come on, dear.

402
00:49:34,118 --> 00:49:35,100
Come on, Yuri.

403
00:49:35,174 --> 00:49:36,155
Sorry.

404
00:49:37,605 --> 00:49:40,322
Well, my dear, that's it.

405
00:49:41,221 --> 00:49:42,682
That's it. Good.

406
00:49:42,821 --> 00:49:43,836
Good.

407
00:49:45,093 --> 00:49:46,304
Good.

408
00:49:53,604 --> 00:49:55,131
Is she going to live?

409
00:49:56,740 --> 00:49:57,788
Water.

410
00:50:03,877 --> 00:50:05,917
- She is, isn't she?
- Yes.

411
00:50:07,237 --> 00:50:08,316
Funny thing.

412
00:50:08,389 --> 00:50:11,291
There's a man, speaks on public platforms.

413
00:50:11,588 --> 00:50:15,101
In with the government.
In with the Liberals. In with everybody.

414
00:50:15,396 --> 00:50:16,804
And he risks it all.

415
00:50:17,222 --> 00:50:18,399
For that!

416
00:50:19,429 --> 00:50:21,535
That's not how poets see them, is it?

417
00:50:21,606 --> 00:50:23,460
That's how GPs see them.

418
00:50:23,942 --> 00:50:25,349
That's how they are.

419
00:50:26,309 --> 00:50:28,676
You know, from here, she looks beautiful.

420
00:50:29,285 --> 00:50:31,521
Zhivago, I think you're a hard case.

421
00:50:36,838 --> 00:50:39,685
There's a child in the case.
A child. Her daughter.

422
00:50:39,749 --> 00:50:41,637
Oh, for heaven's sake, Boris--

423
00:50:42,086 --> 00:50:44,987
She might have thought about "Lara"
before she did it.

424
00:50:45,444 --> 00:50:46,590
Does the girl know?

425
00:50:46,661 --> 00:50:48,068
I'm afraid she does.

426
00:50:48,772 --> 00:50:50,496
- Is she here?
- Yes.

427
00:50:51,429 --> 00:50:53,851
Tell her that her mother's going to live.

428
00:50:54,981 --> 00:50:57,315
Wait a minute, Victor. Yurian.

429
00:50:57,541 --> 00:50:58,818
Yes, of course.

430
00:51:00,933 --> 00:51:03,071
What are we going to say about this?

431
00:51:04,324 --> 00:51:05,951
- Must we say anything?
- I'm afraid so.

432
00:51:06,022 --> 00:51:08,956
I'm taking her to the hospital.
We'll have to say something.

433
00:51:09,062 --> 00:51:11,451
You know that needn't be difficult, Boris.

434
00:53:37,286 --> 00:53:39,839
- What is the name of your assistant?
- Zhivago.

435
00:53:40,070 --> 00:53:41,248
Andreyevich?

436
00:53:41,318 --> 00:53:43,390
Yes, why? Do you know him?

437
00:53:43,975 --> 00:53:46,244
No, I knew his father slightly.

438
00:53:46,662 --> 00:53:47,610
Fine.

439
00:53:57,286 --> 00:54:00,635
Cheer up, Yuri. I'll have the poor bitch
in hospital tonight.

440
00:54:00,838 --> 00:54:02,180
What's his name?

441
00:54:03,079 --> 00:54:05,892
That's Victor Komarovsky.
He says he knows you.

442
00:54:06,214 --> 00:54:08,188
He executed my father's will.

443
00:54:08,838 --> 00:54:10,626
Uncle Alex turned it down.

444
00:54:10,950 --> 00:54:13,251
By Komarovsky's account
there wasn't much in it.

445
00:54:13,318 --> 00:54:15,390
And what there was
belonged to Komarovsky.

446
00:54:15,462 --> 00:54:17,470
Oh, he's a very good businessman.

447
00:54:17,958 --> 00:54:19,781
But I doubt that he's crooked.

448
00:54:20,134 --> 00:54:22,501
Very good company. Knows life.

449
00:54:23,622 --> 00:54:25,532
He's had a bad scare tonight.

450
00:54:43,430 --> 00:54:45,918
You don't mind coming here, do you,
Victor Yppolitovich?

451
00:54:45,990 --> 00:54:48,543
No, no. It reminds me of my youth.

452
00:54:51,526 --> 00:54:53,631
- I went to the hospital again.
- And?

453
00:54:54,629 --> 00:54:58,044
She wants you to go and forgive her.
For her suspicions.

454
00:54:58,117 --> 00:55:00,419
You can tell her the truth
if you like, Larissa.

455
00:55:06,950 --> 00:55:08,030
Is this him?

456
00:55:08,262 --> 00:55:09,278
Yes.

457
00:55:09,703 --> 00:55:11,524
- He knows nothing about--
- No.

458
00:55:17,895 --> 00:55:20,382
Pasha, this is Monsieur Komarovsky.

459
00:55:23,526 --> 00:55:25,119
Please.

460
00:55:32,871 --> 00:55:34,725
- Will you eat?
- No, thank you.

461
00:55:35,206 --> 00:55:38,272
I hope you don't think this is impertinent,
Pavel Pavlovich.

462
00:55:38,342 --> 00:55:39,324
Not at all.

463
00:55:39,398 --> 00:55:42,879
I am...I have been advising
Larissa's mother for many years.

464
00:55:43,207 --> 00:55:44,994
I'm interested in what happens to her.

465
00:55:45,061 --> 00:55:47,134
There's something I have to tell you.
And that is this:

466
00:55:48,678 --> 00:55:50,882
I am committed to the Revolution.

467
00:55:51,238 --> 00:55:52,350
Nothing...

468
00:55:53,190 --> 00:55:56,703
...not even Lara,
has more importance for me.

469
00:55:58,695 --> 00:56:00,069
You misunderstand.

470
00:56:00,774 --> 00:56:02,716
Your political views do not concern me.

471
00:56:02,790 --> 00:56:06,107
So far as that goes, I'm probably
more in sympathy than you suppose.

472
00:56:06,182 --> 00:56:09,216
I have a few contacts of my own,
which might surprise you.

473
00:56:09,831 --> 00:56:11,238
How do you propose to live?

474
00:56:11,303 --> 00:56:13,026
I've been offered a teaching post.

475
00:56:13,094 --> 00:56:15,877
- May I know where?
- Gradov. It's in the Urals.

476
00:56:15,943 --> 00:56:18,146
I know it. Not much of a place.

477
00:56:18,310 --> 00:56:20,644
It's beautiful country,
Monsieur Komarovsky.

478
00:56:20,710 --> 00:56:22,685
It'll be a quiet life, won't it?

479
00:56:23,078 --> 00:56:24,507
That's what we want.

480
00:56:24,647 --> 00:56:27,942
Well, you'll excuse me.
Will your salary be adequate?

481
00:56:28,039 --> 00:56:29,632
Adequate. If not more.

482
00:56:33,287 --> 00:56:37,443
Pavel Pavlovich, my chief impression is,
and I mean no offense...

483
00:56:37,958 --> 00:56:39,518
...is that you're very young.

484
00:56:39,590 --> 00:56:42,143
Monsieur Komarovsky,
I hope I don't offend you.

485
00:56:42,310 --> 00:56:43,968
Do people improve with age?

486
00:56:44,582 --> 00:56:46,274
They grow a little more tolerant.

487
00:56:46,343 --> 00:56:48,732
Because they have more
to tolerate in themselves.

488
00:56:48,871 --> 00:56:51,870
If people don't marry young,
what do they bring to their marriage?

489
00:56:52,102 --> 00:56:54,110
A little experience.

490
00:56:54,503 --> 00:56:58,180
I'm 26. My mother died, needlessly,
when I was eight.

491
00:56:58,343 --> 00:57:01,474
My father died in prison.
I have fended for myself.

492
00:57:01,543 --> 00:57:04,129
I've worked my way
through higher school and university.

493
00:57:04,199 --> 00:57:07,134
I am familiar with things
that you can hardly guess at.

494
00:57:07,399 --> 00:57:09,886
All this is an experience
of a kind, certainly.

495
00:57:10,502 --> 00:57:12,924
I've no amorous experience,
if that's what you mean.

496
00:57:12,999 --> 00:57:16,708
None whatever. Lara's 17.
That speaks for itself.

497
00:57:17,607 --> 00:57:20,291
You probably find this situation comic.
We don't.

498
00:57:20,455 --> 00:57:22,756
We're going to be married next year.

499
00:57:30,182 --> 00:57:32,550
I hope I haven't offended you
by speaking plainly.

500
00:57:32,615 --> 00:57:34,142
Not at all. Admirable.

501
00:57:42,374 --> 00:57:43,781
A young crusader.

502
00:57:43,911 --> 00:57:45,089
Oh, he's not--

503
00:57:45,159 --> 00:57:48,093
He's a very fine young man.
That's obvious.

504
00:57:49,319 --> 00:57:51,686
You're very generous,
Monsieur Komarovsky.

505
00:57:54,727 --> 00:57:56,637
Larissa, I want to talk to you.

506
00:58:05,670 --> 00:58:07,613
Monsieur Komarovsky, will you--

507
00:58:08,294 --> 00:58:09,855
I beg you.

508
00:58:09,927 --> 00:58:13,156
Drop this affectation of addressing me
as "Monsieur Komarovsky"!

509
00:58:13,447 --> 00:58:16,380
Under the circumstances,
I find it rather ridiculous.

510
00:58:16,582 --> 00:58:20,194
Lara, I am determined to save you
from a dreadful error.

511
00:58:20,711 --> 00:58:24,509
There are two kinds of men, and only two.
And that young man is one kind.

512
00:58:24,615 --> 00:58:26,884
He is high-minded. He is pure.

513
00:58:27,208 --> 00:58:31,101
He is the kind of man that the world
pretends to look up to and despises.

514
00:58:31,911 --> 00:58:36,286
He's the kind of man who breeds
unhappiness, particularly in women.

515
00:58:36,455 --> 00:58:37,764
- Do you understand?
- No.

516
00:58:37,831 --> 00:58:38,976
I think you do.

517
00:58:39,816 --> 00:58:41,343
There's another kind.

518
00:58:41,543 --> 00:58:44,859
Not high-minded. Not pure, but alive.

519
00:58:45,576 --> 00:58:49,536
That your tastes at this time should incline
toward the juvenile is understandable.

520
00:58:49,607 --> 00:58:52,607
But, for you to marry that boy
would be a disaster.

521
00:58:52,871 --> 00:58:55,042
Because, there are two kinds of women.

522
00:58:56,391 --> 00:59:00,450
There are two kinds of women and you,
as we well know, are not the first kind.

523
00:59:04,710 --> 00:59:08,006
You, my dear, are a slut.

524
00:59:09,223 --> 00:59:10,717
I am not!

525
00:59:12,039 --> 00:59:13,218
We'll see.

526
00:59:56,070 --> 00:59:58,492
And, don't delude yourself
that this was rape.

527
00:59:58,567 --> 01:00:00,389
That would flatter us both.

528
01:00:43,719 --> 01:00:45,507
The master's not at home, Miss Lara.

529
01:00:45,575 --> 01:00:46,720
Not at home?

530
01:00:46,791 --> 01:00:49,792
No. He went to
the Sventytskis' Christmas party.

531
01:00:52,264 --> 01:00:54,053
Are you going there, Miss?

532
01:00:55,081 --> 01:00:56,903
Please don't say I told you.

533
01:00:57,128 --> 01:00:58,557
No, thank you, Piotr.

534
01:00:58,761 --> 01:01:00,703
Merry Christmas, Miss Lara.

535
01:01:01,928 --> 01:01:04,099
Oh, thank you,
and Merry Christmas to you.

536
01:01:09,928 --> 01:01:12,001
Merry Christmas, Yuri Andreyevich.

537
01:01:52,264 --> 01:01:53,573
What's the matter?

538
01:01:57,576 --> 01:02:00,195
We had an appointment this evening.
Where are you going?

539
01:02:00,264 --> 01:02:02,402
Haven't you got the letter? I left a letter--

540
01:02:02,472 --> 01:02:04,742
I've not been home. I'm going home, now.

541
01:02:06,665 --> 01:02:09,314
Where're you going, Lara?
I've a right to know.

542
01:02:09,704 --> 01:02:11,198
What's in this letter?

543
01:02:12,776 --> 01:02:14,303
What's in this letter?

544
01:02:17,672 --> 01:02:18,784
Are you breaking--

545
01:02:18,855 --> 01:02:20,546
- It's all in the letter.
- What is?

546
01:02:20,616 --> 01:02:21,761
Everything.

547
01:02:22,376 --> 01:02:23,489
Don't!

548
01:03:25,833 --> 01:03:28,550
Yuri, there's an extraordinary girl
at this party.

549
01:03:29,001 --> 01:03:30,823
I know. I'm dancing with her.

550
01:03:33,192 --> 01:03:34,752
You're keen tonight, Victor.

551
01:03:34,824 --> 01:03:36,101
I like to win.

552
01:03:36,488 --> 01:03:37,503
Silence!

553
01:03:37,640 --> 01:03:40,640
Silence, everybody! Silence, please!

554
01:03:41,449 --> 01:03:44,482
I have a very delightful announcement
to make.

555
01:03:47,176 --> 01:03:48,671
Oh, Madame Sventytski!

556
01:03:48,905 --> 01:03:50,081
Yes. Why not?

557
01:03:51,272 --> 01:03:54,206
I have to announce that Dr. Yuri Zhivago--

558
01:03:55,080 --> 01:03:57,666
Doctor Zhivago,
he came third in all Moscow.

559
01:04:00,201 --> 01:04:02,208
Now, listen, please!

560
01:04:02,377 --> 01:04:04,799
Dr. Zhivago is betrothed in marriage to--

561
01:04:27,337 --> 01:04:28,798
My dear Victor!

562
01:04:30,088 --> 01:04:31,266
My dear man!

563
01:04:31,465 --> 01:04:32,675
Get her out.

564
01:04:33,225 --> 01:04:34,173
What?

565
01:04:34,281 --> 01:04:36,550
Get her out. Get her out!

566
01:04:37,096 --> 01:04:38,984
Yes. Yes. I'll get the police.

567
01:04:39,049 --> 01:04:40,030
No!

568
01:04:40,488 --> 01:04:42,244
I don't want you to get the police.

569
01:04:42,888 --> 01:04:45,922
I do not want the police.
I just want you to get her out!

570
01:05:04,009 --> 01:05:05,187
Let her go!

571
01:05:28,617 --> 01:05:29,565
Please!

572
01:05:29,672 --> 01:05:32,160
Quiet, please. Please. Give way.

573
01:05:32,232 --> 01:05:34,120
Please, would you mind?

574
01:05:35,145 --> 01:05:37,250
Would you mind? Thank you, thank you.

575
01:05:49,417 --> 01:05:51,686
Our destinies seem to be interwoven,
don't they?

576
01:05:51,753 --> 01:05:52,615
Yes.

577
01:05:53,321 --> 01:05:55,460
I was a close friend of your father.

578
01:05:56,169 --> 01:05:58,308
I knew you were his business partner.

579
01:05:58,378 --> 01:06:01,476
Rather more than that.
I was present at his death.

580
01:06:03,656 --> 01:06:06,023
Also, I am in contact with your brother.

581
01:06:06,697 --> 01:06:07,428
Yevgraf?.

582
01:06:07,497 --> 01:06:10,246
I should say I'm in contact with those
who are in contact with him.

583
01:06:10,313 --> 01:06:12,419
Oh, I disagree with Bolshevism.

584
01:06:12,809 --> 01:06:13,824
Thank you.

585
01:06:15,145 --> 01:06:16,968
You seem to know your trade.

586
01:06:17,130 --> 01:06:20,227
But, I can still admire Bolsheviks, as men.

587
01:06:21,896 --> 01:06:23,969
Shall I tell you why?

588
01:06:24,201 --> 01:06:25,216
Yes.

589
01:06:27,144 --> 01:06:28,421
They may win.

590
01:06:31,274 --> 01:06:33,478
I'd like to meet him, Yevgraf.

591
01:06:33,866 --> 01:06:35,753
He sent me a marvelous letter.

592
01:06:36,330 --> 01:06:37,791
He likes my poetry.

593
01:06:38,697 --> 01:06:40,836
That would have pleased your father.

594
01:06:41,417 --> 01:06:44,833
Your father was not a bad man, Yuri.
If I may call you Yuri?

595
01:06:45,193 --> 01:06:46,720
I hardly knew him.

596
01:06:48,329 --> 01:06:50,402
You perhaps may not credit this...

597
01:06:51,722 --> 01:06:53,860
...but he was devoted to your mother.

598
01:07:07,369 --> 01:07:10,717
I suppose I may continue to rely
on your professional discretion?

599
01:07:14,536 --> 01:07:18,759
You mean, will I tell anyone the truth
about that girl?

600
01:07:19,594 --> 01:07:21,317
That's what I mean, yes.

601
01:07:23,306 --> 01:07:27,266
You may continue to rely
on my professional etcetera.

602
01:07:27,977 --> 01:07:29,886
You are fastidious, aren't you?

603
01:07:31,177 --> 01:07:34,593
What happens to a girl like that,
when a man like you is finished with her?

604
01:07:35,882 --> 01:07:37,092
Interested?

605
01:07:38,122 --> 01:07:39,431
I give her to you.

606
01:07:42,602 --> 01:07:45,089
You shouldn't smoke. You've had a shock.

607
01:07:51,881 --> 01:07:54,369
I give her to you, Yuri Andreyevich.

608
01:07:55,465 --> 01:07:56,872
A wedding present.

609
01:09:07,434 --> 01:09:09,408
Where have you seen that girl before?

610
01:09:10,122 --> 01:09:12,162
What makes you think
I've seen her before?

611
01:09:12,234 --> 01:09:13,444
Haven't you?

612
01:09:14,410 --> 01:09:16,036
- Yes.
- Where?

613
01:09:16,586 --> 01:09:19,718
I'm not supposed to say.
It was on a case. Not very nice.

614
01:09:19,883 --> 01:09:22,600
No, don't tell me,
if you're not supposed to say.

615
01:10:01,002 --> 01:10:04,351
In bourgeols terms It was a war
between the Allles and Germany.

616
01:10:04,907 --> 01:10:09,031
In Bolshevlk terms It was a war between
the Allled and the German upper classes.

617
01:10:09,451 --> 01:10:12,550
And, whlch of them won was
a matter ofIndlfference.

618
01:10:29,034 --> 01:10:33,540
I was ordered by the Party to enllst.
