642
01:11:45,355 --> 01:11:47,592
...these were the lucky ones.

643
01:11:52,619 --> 01:11:54,081
Even Comrade Lenln...

644
01:11:54,474 --> 01:11:58,664
...underestlmated both
the angulsh of that 900- mlle- long front...

645
01:11:59,466 --> 01:12:01,954
...and our cursed capaclty for sufferlng.

646
01:12:04,682 --> 01:12:07,301
By the second wInter of the war...

647
01:12:07,787 --> 01:12:09,674
...the boots had worn out...

648
01:12:10,955 --> 01:12:12,646
...but the llne stlll held.

649
01:12:13,675 --> 01:12:16,490
Thelr great coats fell to pleces
on thelr backs.

650
01:12:17,483 --> 01:12:19,491
Thelr ratlons were Irregular.

651
01:12:20,427 --> 01:12:22,980
Half of them went lnto actlon
wlthout arms...

652
01:12:23,371 --> 01:12:25,281
...led by men they dldn't trust.

653
01:12:25,355 --> 01:12:27,527
Come on, you bastards!

654
01:12:29,003 --> 01:12:30,628
And, those they dld trust--

655
01:12:30,698 --> 01:12:32,641
Come on, Comrades. Come on!

656
01:12:33,451 --> 01:12:34,433
Come on!

657
01:12:44,075 --> 01:12:45,448
Come on!

658
01:12:47,851 --> 01:12:48,963
Come on!

659
01:12:49,419 --> 01:12:52,004
Comrades! Earthshakers!

660
01:12:52,266 --> 01:12:54,274
Show them!

661
01:12:56,395 --> 01:12:58,337
Charge!

662
01:13:18,923 --> 01:13:23,047
At last they dld what all the armles
dreamed of dolng:

663
01:13:24,043 --> 01:13:25,952
They began to go home.

664
01:13:36,043 --> 01:13:38,498
That was the beglnnlng of the Revolutlon.

665
01:14:02,508 --> 01:14:03,937
Deserters.

666
01:14:04,363 --> 01:14:05,792
Replacements.

667
01:14:18,027 --> 01:14:21,376
Tote arms!

668
01:14:28,779 --> 01:14:29,924
Come back.

669
01:14:31,147 --> 01:14:32,805
Stick together!

670
01:14:35,787 --> 01:14:37,991
Stick together and we'll be all right.

671
01:14:39,117 --> 01:14:40,775
And be ready for them.

672
01:15:05,419 --> 01:15:06,729
Turn around, lads!

673
01:15:06,988 --> 01:15:09,409
- Don't go any farther.
- Come on, lads. Turn around.

674
01:15:09,484 --> 01:15:11,721
Pigs to the slaughter! Look at you!

675
01:15:11,948 --> 01:15:13,377
Turn around, lads.

676
01:15:34,444 --> 01:15:35,654
Listen, lads.

677
01:15:36,460 --> 01:15:38,762
Ten miles up that road are the Germans!

678
01:15:40,459 --> 01:15:42,248
- Rubbish.
- Not rubbish.

679
01:15:42,348 --> 01:15:45,217
They're coming. And they're coming fast.

680
01:15:46,156 --> 01:15:47,683
You've let them in.

681
01:15:49,900 --> 01:15:51,809
They're coming for your wives...

682
01:15:51,947 --> 01:15:54,151
...your houses, your country.

683
01:15:54,284 --> 01:15:56,618
Your country, Officer!

684
01:15:57,387 --> 01:16:00,289
Yes, my country! And proud--

685
01:16:14,764 --> 01:16:16,390
Get back in your ranks!

686
01:16:17,229 --> 01:16:18,756
Get back in your ranks!

687
01:16:24,332 --> 01:16:25,739
Get back!

688
01:16:28,524 --> 01:16:30,596
Get back in the ranks!

689
01:17:43,564 --> 01:17:44,841
Are you a nurse?

690
01:17:45,644 --> 01:17:46,537
Yes.

691
01:17:46,635 --> 01:17:48,228
- Are you all right?
- Yes.

692
01:17:48,940 --> 01:17:50,282
Then help me.

693
01:18:17,261 --> 01:18:20,489
Doctor, I ought to tell you,
I'm not a trained nurse, I'm a volunteer.

694
01:18:20,556 --> 01:18:21,701
I see. Right.

695
01:18:22,604 --> 01:18:24,130
Why did you volunteer?

696
01:18:24,812 --> 01:18:27,627
- I came here to find my husband.
- Very gently.

697
01:18:28,045 --> 01:18:30,314
- Have you ever seen an operation?
- Yes.

698
01:18:30,477 --> 01:18:31,687
We'll manage.

699
01:18:43,757 --> 01:18:47,106
They're in the next village, brothers.
The Germans.

700
01:18:48,301 --> 01:18:49,927
- Your Honor--
- Keep still.

701
01:19:18,765 --> 01:19:20,619
Did you find your husband?

702
01:19:21,997 --> 01:19:22,945
No.

703
01:19:23,053 --> 01:19:24,329
Your Honor...

704
01:19:24,461 --> 01:19:26,054
Yes, we'd better be off.

705
01:19:41,806 --> 01:19:44,619
You know, you often look at me
as though you knew me.

706
01:19:44,812 --> 01:19:47,846
I have seen you.
Four years ago. Christmas Eve.

707
01:19:50,125 --> 01:19:51,619
Were you there?

708
01:19:52,525 --> 01:19:54,151
No wonder you look at me.

709
01:19:56,045 --> 01:19:57,955
Did you know Victor Komarovsky?

710
01:19:58,573 --> 01:20:01,638
Yes, I did. That young man,
who took you away--

711
01:20:01,740 --> 01:20:02,601
My husband.

712
01:20:02,668 --> 01:20:05,702
A lot of courage.
He made the rest of us look very feeble.

713
01:20:05,772 --> 01:20:08,292
As a matter of fact, I thought you both did.

714
01:20:08,620 --> 01:20:10,279
Good man to shoot at.

715
01:20:11,277 --> 01:20:13,579
I'd give anything never to have met him.

716
01:20:42,606 --> 01:20:44,231
The tsar's in prison.

717
01:20:46,125 --> 01:20:47,587
Lenin's in Moscow.

718
01:20:49,006 --> 01:20:50,695
Civil war has started.

719
01:20:51,085 --> 01:20:52,012
Good!

720
01:20:52,076 --> 01:20:53,571
Civil war, good?

721
01:20:54,444 --> 01:20:56,550
Not good, Comrade Nurse, inevitable.

722
01:20:58,124 --> 01:21:00,994
But Lenin in Moscow!

723
01:21:01,645 --> 01:21:04,994
This Lenin, will he be the new tsar then?

724
01:21:06,061 --> 01:21:09,356
Listen, Daddy.
No more tsars, no more masters.

725
01:21:09,645 --> 01:21:12,907
Only workers in a worker's state.
How about that?

726
01:21:14,189 --> 01:21:15,618
Are you a doctor?

727
01:21:15,821 --> 01:21:17,447
- Yes.
- Follow me, please.

728
01:22:02,382 --> 01:22:04,237
I can't deal with this.

729
01:22:04,750 --> 01:22:08,099
Order of the Provisional Government.
You'll have to try, friend.

730
01:22:15,917 --> 01:22:18,471
"If you could see how hard
we have been working here...

731
01:22:18,541 --> 01:22:21,858
"...I feel sure you'd forgive me, dear,
for not writing more regularly."

732
01:22:21,934 --> 01:22:23,243
When was that written?

733
01:22:23,342 --> 01:22:24,552
July 20th.

734
01:22:24,621 --> 01:22:25,734
Eight weeks!

735
01:22:26,286 --> 01:22:28,872
"But now the war seems
really to have stopped.

736
01:22:28,942 --> 01:22:32,072
"The hospital is emptying,
and I shall have more time.

737
01:22:32,173 --> 01:22:36,330
"I may even get time to write some verse,
if I've not forgotten how to."

738
01:22:36,909 --> 01:22:38,316
Oh, I do hope so!

739
01:22:40,493 --> 01:22:43,908
"Larissa Antipova is still here,
and I admire her more and more.

740
01:22:45,582 --> 01:22:49,772
"She seems to have the strange gift
of healing, which doctors don't believe in.

741
01:22:50,478 --> 01:22:54,253
"She often does the wrong things,
but it always seems to work out right.

742
01:22:55,822 --> 01:22:57,229
"How is Uncle Alex?

743
01:22:57,390 --> 01:23:00,652
- "Can he still get his English tobacco?"
- Would that he could!

744
01:23:00,718 --> 01:23:03,752
"Can Sasha say his letters yet?
And how is Auntie Anna?"

745
01:23:05,293 --> 01:23:07,082
He didn't get my letter.

746
01:23:08,206 --> 01:23:10,595
"Most of all, my dearest, how are you?"

747
01:23:11,182 --> 01:23:13,735
Strangely upsetting.
He doesn't know she's dead.

748
01:23:14,958 --> 01:23:16,998
Can't see what difference it makes.

749
01:23:18,318 --> 01:23:19,725
They're at it again!

750
01:23:20,398 --> 01:23:22,786
I wish they'd decide once and for all...

751
01:23:23,373 --> 01:23:27,945
...which gang of hooligans constitutes
the government of this country!

752
01:23:34,510 --> 01:23:35,917
Cheer up, Sergei.

753
01:23:36,751 --> 01:23:38,408
Don't you want to go home?

754
01:23:39,149 --> 01:23:41,899
There's fighting at home, Your Honor.
I've had enough.

755
01:23:42,510 --> 01:23:46,307
Red Guards and White Guards,
this old man's had enough.

756
01:23:47,726 --> 01:23:49,636
Your Honor is a kind gentleman.

757
01:23:52,271 --> 01:23:54,441
And, the nurse is a kind lady.

758
01:24:08,846 --> 01:24:09,959
Finished?

759
01:24:10,190 --> 01:24:11,466
Just about.

760
01:24:20,077 --> 01:24:22,630
In a couple of weeks
you'll be with your little girl.

761
01:24:22,701 --> 01:24:24,295
If I can get on a train.

762
01:24:27,183 --> 01:24:30,216
I want to be with Katya
more than anything in the world.

763
01:24:30,478 --> 01:24:31,689
Yes, of course.

764
01:24:33,134 --> 01:24:35,338
But, now that we're going, I feel sad.

765
01:24:37,422 --> 01:24:38,371
Sad.

766
01:24:39,663 --> 01:24:40,710
Really sad.

767
01:24:41,327 --> 01:24:43,563
- Well, we've been here some time.
- Yes.

768
01:24:46,126 --> 01:24:48,515
This must have been a lovely house, once.

769
01:24:49,422 --> 01:24:50,535
Don't you think?

770
01:24:50,606 --> 01:24:52,297
What are you going to do?

771
01:24:52,974 --> 01:24:54,021
In Gradov?

772
01:24:54,094 --> 01:24:55,042
Yes.

773
01:24:56,238 --> 01:24:57,286
I'll be all right.

774
01:24:57,359 --> 01:24:58,952
I wish I could think so.

775
01:25:04,622 --> 01:25:06,215
You could run a laundry.

776
01:25:07,821 --> 01:25:09,250
What will you do?

777
